Definition 2.3. A non-$\Sigma$ relative 2-operad in a category $\mathcal{C}$ with finite limits is a pair $\displaystyle\Bigl{(}(P_{r})_{r\geq 1},(Q_{\mathbf{m}})_{\mathbf{m}\in\mathbb{% Z}^{r}_{\geq 0}\setminus\{\mathbf{0}\},r\geq 1}\Bigr{)},$ where $(P_{r})_{r\geq 1}$ is a non-$\Sigma$ operad in $\mathcal{C}$ with structure morphisms $\gamma_{r,(s_{i})}$, and where $(Q_{\mathbf{m}})\subset\mathcal{C}$ is a collection of objects together with a family of structure morphisms $\displaystyle\Gamma_{\mathbf{m},(\mathbf{n}^{a}_{i})}\colon Q_{\mathbf{m}}% \times\prod_{1\leq i\leq r}\prod^{P_{s_{i}}}_{1\leq a\leq m_{i}}Q_{\mathbf{n}_% {i}^{a}}\to Q_{\sum_{a}\mathbf{n}_{1}^{a},\ldots,\sum_{a}\mathbf{n}_{r}^{a}},% \quad r,s_{1},\ldots s_{r}\geq 1,\mathbf{m}\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}^{r}\setminus% \{\mathbf{0}\},\mathbf{n}_{i}^{a}\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}^{s_{i}}\setminus\{% \mathbf{0}\}$ which satisfy the following axioms. (projections) $\bigl{(}(P_{r}),(Q_{\mathbf{m}})\bigr{)}$ is equipped with projection morphisms $\displaystyle\pi_{\mathbf{m}}\colon Q_{\mathbf{m}}\to P_{r},\qquad r\geq 1,\>% \mathbf{m}\in\mathbb{Z}^{r}_{\geq 0}\setminus\{\mathbf{0}\}$ such that the following diagram commutes: $\displaystyle 2\operatorname{Mor}(x_{0},x_{r})\ar^{(s,t)}[d]$ $\displaystyle\xymatrix$$\displaystyle 2\operatorname{Mor}(x_{0},x_{r})\ar^{(s,t)}[d]$
Definition 3.1. (Syntax of values of $\Pi$) $\begin{array}[]{rclr}\mathit{values},v&::=&()~{}|~{}\mathit{left}~{}v~{}|~{}% \mathit{right}~{}v~{}|~{}(v,v)\\ \end{array}$
Definition 3.2 (Propositional Equivalence). Two expressions $a,b$ of type $A$ are propositionally equal if their normal forms are equivalent under the rules of the host type system.
Definition 3.4 (Quasi-inverse). For a function $f:A\rightarrow B$, a quasi-inverse is a triple $(g,\alpha,\beta)$, consisting of a function $g:B\rightarrow A$ and two homotopies $\alpha:f\circ g\sim\mathrm{id}_{B}$ and $\beta:g\circ f\sim\mathrm{id}_{A}$.
Definition 2.1. For $n\in\mathbb{N}$, denote by $\left[n\right]$ the set $\left\{0,1,\ldots,n-1\right\}$. We will refer to $\left[n\right]$ as the canonical set with $n$ elements.
Definition 3.3 (Adjoint, $!~{}c$). The adjoint of a combinator $c$ is defined as follows: • For primitive isomorphisms $c$, $!~{}c$ is given by its inverse from Figs. 2 and 5. • $!(c_{1}\otimes c_{2})=\ !c_{1}\otimes~{}!c_{2}$ • $!(c_{1}\oplus c_{2})=\ !c_{1}\oplus~{}!c_{2}$ • $!(c_{1}\odot c_{2})=\ !c_{2}\odot~{}!c_{1}$. (Note that the order of combinators has been reversed).
Definition 3.6 (Bi-invertibility). For a function $f:A\rightarrow B$, a bi-inverse is a pair of functions $g,h:B\rightarrow A$ and two homotopies $\alpha:f\circ g\sim\mathrm{id}_{B}$ and $\beta:h\circ f\sim\mathrm{id}_{A}$.
Definition 3.2. (Operational Semantics for $\Pi$) Identity: $\begin{array}[]{rlcl}\mathit{id}\!\!\leftrightarrow&v&\mapsto&v\\ \end{array}$ Additive fragment: $\begin{array}[]{rlcl}\mathit{unite}_{+}\mathit{l}&(\mathit{right}~{}v)&\mapsto% &v\\ \mathit{uniti}_{+}\mathit{l}&v&\mapsto&\mathit{right}~{}v\\ \mathit{unite}_{+}\mathit{r}&(\mathit{left}~{}v)&\mapsto&v\\ \mathit{uniti}_{+}\mathit{r}&v&\mapsto&\mathit{left}~{}v\\ \mathit{swap}_{+}&(\mathit{left}~{}v)&\mapsto&\mathit{right}~{}v\\ \mathit{swap}_{+}&(\mathit{right}~{}v)&\mapsto&\mathit{left}~{}v\\ \mathit{assocl}_{+}&(\mathit{left}~{}v_{1})&\mapsto&\mathit{left}~{}(\mathit{% left}~{}v_{1})\\ \mathit{assocl}_{+}&(\mathit{right}~{}(\mathit{left}~{}v_{2}))&\mapsto&\mathit% {left}~{}(\mathit{right}~{}v_{2})\\ \mathit{assocl}_{+}&(\mathit{right}~{}(\mathit{right}~{}v_{3}))&\mapsto&% \mathit{right}~{}v_{3}\\ \mathit{assocr}_{+}&(\mathit{left}~{}(\mathit{left}~{}v_{1}))&\mapsto&\mathit{% left}~{}v_{1}\\ \mathit{assocr}_{+}&(\mathit{left}~{}(\mathit{right}~{}v_{2}))&\mapsto&\mathit% {right}~{}(\mathit{left}~{}v_{2})\\ \mathit{assocr}_{+}&(\mathit{right}~{}v_{3})&\mapsto&\mathit{right}~{}(\mathit% {right}~{}v_{3})\\ \end{array}$ Multiplicative fragment: $\begin{array}[]{rlcl}\mathit{unite}_{\times}\mathit{l}&((),v)&\mapsto&v\\ \mathit{uniti}_{\times}\mathit{l}&v&\mapsto&((),v)\\ \mathit{unite}_{\times}\mathit{r}&(v,())&\mapsto&v\\ \mathit{uniti}_{\times}\mathit{r}&v&\mapsto&(v,())\\ \mathit{swap}_{\times}&(v_{1},v_{2})&\mapsto&(v_{2},v_{1})\\ \mathit{assocl}_{\times}&(v_{1},(v_{2},v_{3}))&\mapsto&((v_{1},v_{2}),v_{3})\\ \mathit{assocr}_{\times}&((v_{1},v_{2}),v_{3})&\mapsto&(v_{1},(v_{2},v_{3}))\\ \mathit{absorbr}&(v_{1},v_{2})&\mapsto&v_{1}\\ \end{array}$ Distributivity and factoring: $\begin{array}[]{rlcl}\mathit{dist}&(\mathit{left}~{}v_{1},v_{3})&\mapsto&% \mathit{left}~{}(v_{1},v_{3})\\ \mathit{dist}&(\mathit{right}~{}v_{2},v_{3})&\mapsto&\mathit{right}~{}(v_{2},v% _{3})\\ \mathit{distl}&(v_{1},\mathit{left}~{}v_{2})&\mapsto&\mathit{left}~{}(v_{1},v_% {2})\\ \mathit{distl}&(v_{1},\mathit{right}~{}v_{3})&\mapsto&\mathit{right}~{}(v_{1},% v_{3})\\ \mathit{factor}&(\mathit{left}~{}(v_{1},v_{3}))&\mapsto&(\mathit{left}~{}v_{1}% ,v_{3})\\ \mathit{factor}&(\mathit{right}~{}(v_{2},v_{3}))&\mapsto&(\mathit{right}~{}v_{% 2},v_{3})\\ \mathit{factorl}&(\mathit{left}~{}(v_{1},v_{2}))&\mapsto&(v_{1},\mathit{left}~% {}v_{2})\\ \mathit{factorl}&(\mathit{right}~{}(v_{1},v_{3}))&\mapsto&(v_{1},\mathit{right% }~{}v_{3})\\ \mathit{absorbl}&(v_{1},v_{2})&\mapsto&v_{2}\\ \end{array}$ The evaluation rules of the composition combinators are given below: $\infer{(c_{1}\odot c_{2})~{}v_{1}\mapsto v_{2}}{c_{1}~{}v_{1}\mapsto v&c_{2}~{% }v\mapsto v_{2}}$ $\infer{(c_{1}\oplus c_{2})~{}(\mathit{left}~{}v_{1})\mapsto\mathit{left}~{}v_{% 2}}{c_{1}~{}v_{1}\mapsto v_{2}}\quad\infer{(c_{1}\oplus c_{2})~{}(\mathit{% right}~{}v_{1})\mapsto\mathit{right}~{}v_{2}}{c_{2}~{}v_{1}\mapsto v_{2}}$ $\infer{(c_{1}\otimes c_{2})~{}(v_{1},v_{2})\mapsto(v_{3},v_{4})}{c_{1}~{}v_{1}% \mapsto v_{3}&c_{2}~{}v_{2}\mapsto v_{4}}$
Definition 3.3 (Homotopy). Two functions $f,g:A\rightarrow B$ are homotopic if $\forall x:A.f(x)\equiv g(x)$. We denote this $f\sim g$.
Definition 3.1. A commutative semiring (sometimes called a commutative rig — commutative ring without negative elements) $(R,0,1,+,\cdot)$ consists of a set $R$, two distinguished elements of $R$ named $0$ and $1$, and two binary operations $+$ and $\cdot$, satisfying the following relations for any $a,b,c\in R$: $\begin{array}[]{rcl}0+a&=&a\\ a+b&=&b+a\\ a+(b+c)&=&(a+b)+c\\ \\ 1\cdot a&=&a\\ a\cdot b&=&b\cdot a\\ a\cdot(b\cdot c)&=&(a\cdot b)\cdot c\\ \\ 0\cdot a&=&0\\ (a+b)\cdot c&=&(a\cdot c)+(b\cdot c)\end{array}$
Definition 3.5 (Equivalence of types). Two types $A$ and $B$ are equivalent $A\simeq B$ if there exists a function $f:A\rightarrow B$ together with a quasi-inverse for $f$.
Definition 3.4. ($\sharp$). By recursion on $|b|$. First define $\tau$ that maps numeric sizes to their corresponding types. We will revert to using type notation for greater clarity of this definition: $\begin{array}[]{rcl}\tau~{}(0)&=&\bot\\ \tau~{}(1+n)&=&\top\uplus\tau~{}(n)\\ \end{array}$ so that we can define $\sharp\,b=\tau~{}|b|$.
Definition 2.21 ($(\Sigma,E)$-algebra) For an algebraic theory $(\Sigma,E)$, a $(\Sigma,E)$-algebra is a $\Sigma$-algebra that satisfies all the equations in $E$. A $(\Sigma,E)$-algebra homomorphism is just a $\Sigma$-algebra homomorphism between $(\Sigma,E)$-algebras. $(\Sigma,E)$-algebras and their homomorphisms form a category $(\Sigma,E)-\mathbf{Alg}$.
Definition 3.2 (Universal Terms) For an algebraic theory, we say that a set of terms $T$ is: • Universal if every term is provably equal to a universal term. • Stable if $T$ is closed under substitution of variables for variables.
Definition 2.16 (Algebraic Theory) An algebraic signature is a set of operation symbols $\Sigma$, each with an associated natural number referred to as its arity. The set of $\Sigma$-terms over a set $X$ of variables is defined inductively as follows: • Each element $x\in X$ is a term. • If $t_{1},...,t_{n}$ are terms, and $\sigma\in\Sigma$ has arity $n$, then $\sigma(t_{1},...,t_{n})$ is a term. An algebraic theory $\mathbb{T}$ consists of: • An algebraic signature $\Sigma^{\mathbb{T}}$. • A set of pairs of $\Sigma$-terms over $X$, $E^{\mathbb{T}}$, referred to as the equations or axioms of $\mathbb{T}$. We will often write a pair $(s,t)\in E^{\mathbb{T}}$ as the more readable $s=t$ when convenient. The following terminology and notational conventions will be used: • Operations of arity $n$, will be referred to as $n$-ary. Operations of arity 1,2 and 3 will be referred to as unary, binary and ternary operations. 0-ary terms will be referred to as constants. • Variable contexts: If $Y\subseteq X$ is a set of variables and $t$ is a term, then we write $Y\vdash t$ to mean that the free variables in $t$ are a subset of $Y$. When we wish to make the algebraic theory of interest explicit, we will write $Y\vdash_{\mathbb{T}}t$ meaning $t$ is a term of the algebraic theory $\mathbb{T}$ in variable context $Y$. • Set of free variables: If we need the precise set of free variables in a term $t$, we write $\operatorname{var}(t)$. In addition, $\#\operatorname{var}(t)$ denotes the cardinality of the set $\operatorname{var}(t)$. • Equality of terms: When two terms $t_{1},t_{2}$ in $\mathbb{T}$ can be proved equal using equational logic and axioms of $\mathbb{T}$ as outlined in Figure 1, we write $t_{1}=_{\mathbb{T}}t_{2}$. When we wish to be specific about which variables may appear in $t_{1}$ and $t_{2}$, we will write: $X\vdash_{\mathbb{T}}t_{1}=t_{2}\qquad\text{ iff }\qquad X\vdash t_{1}\;\text{ % and }\;X\vdash t_{2}\;\text{ and }\;t_{1}=_{\mathbb{T}}t_{2}$ • Substitution: For a term in context $Y\vdash_{\mathbb{T}}t$ and partial function $f$ mapping variables in $Y$ to $\mathbb{T}$-terms, we will write $t[f]$ or $t[f(y)/y]$ for the corresponding substitution of terms for variables where $f$ is defined. • Extended infix and postfix notation: We will extend our notation in the natural way to include infix notation for binary function symbols with symbolic names, for example $a+b$, and postfix notation when it is standard to do so, for example to indicate a multiplicative inverse $a^{-1}$.
Definition 2.26 We will say that monad $T$ corresponds to theory $\mathbb{T}$ or has presentation/is presented by $\mathbb{T}$ if $T$ is a free model monad induced by $\mathbb{T}$. In general, a monad has more than one presentation. Even so, if a certain presentation is commonly used for a monad, we refer to it as the theory corresponding to the monad.
Definition 2.10 (Distributive Law) Given monads $S$ and $T$, a distributive law for monad composition $TS$ is a natural transformation $\lambda:ST\Rightarrow TS$ satisfying the following axioms: $\displaystyle\lambda\cdot\eta^{S}T$ $\displaystyle=T\eta^{S}$ $\displaystyle\lambda\cdot S\eta^{T}$ $\displaystyle=\eta^{T}S$ $\displaystyle\lambda\cdot\mu^{S}T$ $\displaystyle=T\mu^{S}\cdot\lambda S\cdot S\lambda$ $\displaystyle\lambda\cdot S\mu^{T}$ $\displaystyle=\mu^{T}S\cdot T\lambda\cdot\lambda T$ Or, as commuting diagrams: {tikzcd} & T \arrow[dl, ”η^S T”’]\arrow[dr, ”T η^S”] & & SST \arrow[d, ”μ^S T”’] \arrow[r, ”S λ”] & STS \arrow[r, ”λS”] & TSS \arrow[d, ”T μ^S”] ST \arrow[rr, ”λ”]& & TS & ST \arrow[rr,”λ”] & & TS & S \arrow[dl, ”Sη^T”’] \arrow[dr, ”η^T S”] & & STT \arrow[d, ”S μ^T”’] \arrow[r, ”λT”] & TST \arrow[r, ”Tλ”] & TTS \arrow[d, ”μ^T S”] ST \arrow[rr, ”λ”] & & TS & ST \arrow[rr,”λ”] & & TS
Definition 2.20 ($\Sigma$-algebra) For a signature $\Sigma$, a $\Sigma$-algebra consists of: • An underlying set $A$. • For each $n$-ary operation $\sigma\in\Sigma^{\mathbb{T}}$ a function $\llbracket\sigma\rrbracket:A^{n}\rightarrow A$. A homomorphism of $\Sigma$-algebras of type $(A,\llbracket-\rrbracket^{A})\rightarrow(B,\llbracket-\rrbracket^{B})$ is a function $h:A\rightarrow B$ such that for each $n$-ary $\sigma\in\Sigma$: $h(\llbracket\sigma\rrbracket^{A}(x_{1},...,x_{n}))=\llbracket\sigma\rrbracket^% {B}(h(x_{1}),...,h(x_{n}))$ For a fixed $\Sigma$-algebra, every $\Sigma$-term $\{x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}\}\vdash t$ induces a function $\llbracket t\rrbracket:A^{n}\rightarrow A$, defined inductively as follows: • For variable $1\leq i\leq n$: $\llbracket i\rrbracket(x_{1},...,x_{n})=x_{i}$ • For $m$-ary operation $\sigma\in\Sigma$: $\llbracket\sigma(t_{1},...,t_{m})\rrbracket(x_{1},...,x_{n})=\llbracket\sigma% \rrbracket(\llbracket t_{1}\rrbracket(x_{1},...,x_{n}),...,\llbracket t_{m}% \rrbracket(x_{1},...,x_{n}))$ An algebra satisfies equation $\{x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}\}\vdash s=t$ if: $\llbracket s\rrbracket=\llbracket t\rrbracket$
Definition 2.28 (Composite Theories) Let $\mathbb{S}$ and $\mathbb{T}$ be two algebraic theories, and let $\mathbb{U}$ be an algebraic theory that contains both $\mathbb{S}$ and $\mathbb{T}$. Then $\mathbb{U}$ is a composite of $\mathbb{S}$ and $\mathbb{T}$ if it satisfies the following two conditions: 1. Separation: Every term $u$ in $\mathbb{U}$ is equal to a term $t$ in $\mathbb{T}$ built from terms $s_{i}$ in $\mathbb{S}$: $u=_{\mathbb{U}}t[s_{i}/x_{i}]$. 2. Essential uniqueness: The separation of $\mathbb{U}$-terms into $\mathbb{T}$-terms of $\mathbb{S}$-terms is unique modulo $\mathbb{S},\mathbb{T}$. That is, for terms $X\vdash_{\mathbb{T}}t$, $X^{\prime}\vdash_{\mathbb{T}}t^{\prime}$ and $Y_{i}\vdash_{\mathbb{S}}s_{i}$, $Y^{\prime}_{j}\vdash_{\mathbb{S}}s^{\prime}_{j}$ such that $t[s_{i}/x_{i}]=_{\mathbb{U}}t^{\prime}[s^{\prime}_{j}/x^{\prime}_{j}]$, there is a set of variables $Z$ and there are functions $f:X\rightarrow Z$, $f^{\prime}:X^{\prime}\rightarrow Z$ satisfying: (a) $t[f(x_{i})/x_{i}]=_{\mathbb{T}}t^{\prime}[f^{\prime}(x^{\prime}_{j})/x^{\prime% }_{j}]$. (b) For all $i,j$: $f(x_{i})=f^{\prime}(x^{\prime}_{j})$ iff $s_{i}=_{\mathbb{S}}s^{\prime}_{j}$.
Definition 2.1 (Monad) For any category $\mathcal{C}$, a monad $\langle T,\eta,\mu\rangle$ on $\mathcal{C}$ consists of: • An endofunctor $T:\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$. • A natural transformation $\eta:1\Rightarrow T$ called the unit. • A natural transformation $\mu:TT\Rightarrow T$ called the multiplication. such that the following axioms hold: $\displaystyle\mu\cdot T\eta$ $\displaystyle=id$ $\displaystyle\mu\cdot\eta T$ $\displaystyle=id$ $\displaystyle\mu\cdot T\mu$ $\displaystyle=\mu\cdot\mu T$ Or, as commuting diagrams: {tikzcd} TX \arrow[r, ”ηT”]\arrow[d, ”Tη”’] \arrow[rd, equal] & TTX \arrow[d, ”μ”] & & TTTX \arrow[r, ”μT”]\arrow[d, ”T μ”’] & TTX \arrow[d, ”μ”] TTX \arrow[r, ”μ”] & TX & & TTX \arrow[r, ”μ”] & TX
Definition 2.25 (Free model monad) For an algebraic theory $\mathbb{T}$, the free model monad induced by $\mathbb{T}$ is the monad induced by the free/forgetful adjunction $U^{\mathbb{T}}\circ F^{\mathbb{T}}$.
Definition 2.7 A function with codomain the natural numbers or positive reals is said to have finite support if only finitely many elements of $X$ are mapped to non-zero values.
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category with translation functor $\Sigma$. Given three composable morphisms in $\mathcal{T}$ $W\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\longrightarrow}}X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle g}}{{% \longrightarrow}}Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle h}}{{\longrightarrow}}Z,$ such that $gf=0$ and $hg=0$, the Toda bracket $\langle h,g,f\rangle\in\frac{\mathcal{T}(\Sigma W,Z)}{h\cdot\mathcal{T}(\Sigma W% ,Y)+\mathcal{T}(\Sigma X,Z)\cdot(\Sigma f)}$ is defined in the following way. If $W\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\longrightarrow}}X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle i}}{{% \longrightarrow}}C_{f}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle q}}{{\longrightarrow}}\Sigma W$ is an exact triangle in $\mathcal{T}$ the axioms of a triangulated category imply the existence of a commutative diagram $\xymatrix{W\ar[r]^{f}\ar@{=}[d]&X\ar[r]^{i}\ar@{=}[d]&C_{f}\ar[r]^{q}\ar[d]^{a% }&\Sigma W\ar[d]^{b}\\ W\ar[r]_{f}&X\ar[r]_{g}&Y\ar[r]_{h}&Z}$ The morphism $b$ is a representative of the Toda bracket $\langle h,g,f\rangle$. The Toda bracket does not depend on the choices made for its definition since we divide out the indeterminacy. Moreover, all representatives of $\langle h,g,f\rangle$ can be obtained in this way.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category. A $\mathcal{C}$-bimodule $L$ is a functor $L\colon\mathcal{C}^{op}\times\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathbf{Ab}$, where $\mathbf{Ab}$ is the category of abelian groups. The Baues-Wirsching complex $F^{*}(\mathcal{C},L)$ is given by the following products indexed by all sequences of morphisms of length $n$ in $\mathcal{C}$ $\displaystyle F^{n}(\mathcal{C},L)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\prod_{X_{0}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sigma_{1}}}{{\leftarrow}}% \cdots\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sigma_{n}}}{{\leftarrow}}X_{n}}L(X_{n},X_{0}),\;% \;n\geq 0.$ In this formula we assume that a sequence of length $0$ is an object $X_{0}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ which we also identify with the identity morphism $1_{X_{0}}$. The coordinate of $c\in F^{n}(\mathcal{C},L)$ in $X_{0}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sigma_{1}}}{{\leftarrow}}\cdots\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\sigma_{n}}}{{\leftarrow}}X_{n}$ will be denoted by $c(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{n})$. The value of the differential $d$ over an $n$-cochain $c$, $n\geq 1$, is defined as $\displaystyle d(c)(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{n+1})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle L(X_{n+1},\sigma_{1})c(\sigma_{2},\dots,\sigma_{n+1})$ $\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}c(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{i}\sigma_{i+1},% \dots,\sigma_{n+1})$ $\displaystyle+(-1)^{n+1}L(\sigma_{n+1},X_{0})c(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{n}).$ For $n=0$ and $\sigma\colon X\rightarrow Y$, $d(c)(\sigma)=L(1,\sigma)c(X)-L(\sigma,1)c(Y)$. The cohomology of $\mathcal{C}$ with coefficients in $L$ is the cohomology of the complex $F^{*}(\mathcal{C},L)$. It is denoted by $H^{*}(\mathcal{C},L)$. For the functorial behaviour of cohomology of categories see [Mur06]. If the bimodule $L$ takes values in the category of $k$-modules for $k$ a commutative ring then $H^{*}(\mathcal{C},L)$ is a graded $k$-module.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category and let $L$ be a $\mathcal{C}$-bimodule. The Pirashvili-Waldhausen complex $F_{*}(\mathcal{C},L)$ is given by the direct sums $\displaystyle F_{n}(\mathcal{C},L)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\bigoplus_{X_{0}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sigma_{1}}}{{\leftarrow}}% \cdots\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sigma_{n}}}{{\leftarrow}}X_{n}}L(X_{0},X_{n}),\;% \;n\geq 0.$ An element $c\in L(X_{0},X_{n})$ regarded as an $n$-chain in the direct factor correspoding to $X_{0}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sigma_{1}}}{{\leftarrow}}\cdots\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\sigma_{n}}}{{\leftarrow}}X_{n}$ will be denoted by $c\cdot(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{n})$. The differential is defined by $\displaystyle d(c\cdot(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{n}))$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle L(\sigma_{1},X_{n})(c)\cdot(\sigma_{2},\dots,\sigma_{n})$ $\displaystyle+\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}(-1)^{i}c\cdot(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{i}\sigma% _{i+1},\dots,\sigma_{n})$ $\displaystyle+(-1)^{n}L(X_{0},\sigma_{n})(c)\cdot(\sigma_{1},\dots,\sigma_{n-1% }),$ for $n\geq 2$, and for $n=1$ and $\sigma\colon X\rightarrow Y$ we have $d(c\cdot\sigma)=L(\sigma,X)(c)\cdot X-L(Y,\sigma)(c)\cdot Y$. This differential differs from the one defined in [PW92] by a sign. Of course this does not affect the homology. The homology of $\mathcal{C}$ with coefficients in $L$ is the homology of the complex $F_{*}(\mathcal{C},L)$. It is denoted by $H_{*}(\mathcal{C},L)$. If $L$ takes values in the category of $k$-modules for $k$ a commutative ring then $H_{*}(\mathcal{C},L)$ is a graded $k$-module.
Definition 4.3. Given a category $\mathcal{C}$ with zero object $*$, a $\mathcal{C}$-bimodule $L$ with $L(*,-)=0$ and $L(-,*)=0$, and a cohomology class $\zeta\in H^{3}(\mathcal{C},L)$, then the $\zeta$-Toda bracket of a diagram in $\mathcal{C}$ $W\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\longrightarrow}}X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle g}}{{% \longrightarrow}}Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle h}}{{\longrightarrow}}Z,$ with $gf=0$ and $hg=0$, is defined as follows. The diagram corresponds to a functor $\varphi\colon\mathbf{Toda}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ with $\varphi(*)=*$, $\varphi(j_{1})=f$, $\varphi(j_{2})=g$, and $\varphi(j_{2})=h$, and the $\zeta$-Toda bracket is the pull-back along $\varphi$ of the cohomology class $\zeta$ $\langle h,g,f\rangle_{\zeta}\;=\;\varphi^{*}\zeta\;\in\;H^{3}(\mathbf{Toda},L(% \varphi,\varphi))\;\cong\;\frac{L(W,Z)}{L(W,h)L(W,Y)+L(f,Z)L(X,Z)}.$ If $c$ is a cocycle representing $\zeta$ which is normalized with respect to identity and zero morphisms then $\langle h,g,f\rangle_{\zeta}$ is represented by $c(h,g,f)$.
Definition 3.4. Given a current map $(\cdot)_{*}$ on a polygraphic program that satisfies the conditions of example 3.3, the heat map $[\cdot]_{S}$ is called structure heat generated by $(\cdot)_{*}$.
Definition 2.5 (Semantics). Let us fix a polygraphic program $\mathcal{P}$. If $\xi$ is a $1$-cell, a term of type $\mathit{\xi}$ is a $2$-path built only with constructors and with $\xi$ as $1$-target. A value or closed term is a term with no input. The set of values with type $\xi$ is denoted by $\mathcal{V}(\xi)$. The domain of computation of $\mathcal{P}$ is the multi-sorted algebra made of the family of all the sets $\mathcal{V}(\xi)$ equipped with the operations given, for each constructor $\gamma:\xi_{1}\star_{0}\cdots\star_{0}\xi_{n}\Rightarrow\xi$, by the map still denoted by $\gamma$: $\displaystyle\gamma\>:\>\mathcal{V}(\xi_{1})\times\cdots\times\mathcal{V}(\xi_% {n})$ $\displaystyle\to\mathcal{V}(\xi)$ $\displaystyle(t_{1},\dots,t_{n})$ $\displaystyle\mapsto(t_{1}\star_{0}\cdots\star_{0}t_{n})\star_{1}\gamma.$ Let us consider a function $f$ from $\mathcal{V}(\xi_{1})\times\cdots\times\mathcal{V}(\xi_{m})$ to $\mathcal{V}(\zeta_{1})\times\cdots\times\mathcal{V}(\zeta_{n})$. There are two cases whether $\mathcal{P}$ is confluent or not. If $\mathcal{P}$ is confluent, we say that $\mathcal{P}$ computes $f$ if there exists a $2$-path, still denoted by $f$, from $\xi_{1}\star_{0}\cdots\star_{0}\xi_{m}$ to $\zeta_{1}\star_{0}\cdots\star_{0}\zeta_{n}$, such that, for every family $(t_{1},\dots,t_{m})$ of values in $\mathcal{V}(\xi_{1})\times\cdots\times\mathcal{V}(\xi_{m})$, the $2$-path $(t_{1}\star_{0}\dots\star_{0}t_{m})\star_{1}f$ normalizes into the family $f(t_{1},\dots,t_{m})$ of values in $\mathcal{V}(\zeta_{1})\times\cdots\times\mathcal{V}(\zeta_{n})$. Let us note that the normal form is unique in that case. If $\mathcal{P}$ is not confluent, after Gurevich and Grädel [5], we say that it computes $f$ if, for all values $(t_{1},\dots,t_{m})$ in $\mathcal{V}(\xi_{1})\times\cdots\times\mathcal{V}(\xi_{m})$, the following holds, where the considered order is the lexicographic order: $f(t_{1},\dots,t_{m})\>=\>\max\big{\{}\>\text{normal forms of }(t_{1}\star_{0}% \dots\star_{0}t_{m})\star_{1}f\>\big{\}}.$
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{P}$ be a polygraphic program. If $f$ is a $2$-path of $\mathcal{P}$, we denote by $\left|\left|f\right|\right|$ the number of $2$-cells $f$ is made of. If $F$ is a $3$-path of $\mathcal{P}$, we denote by $\left|\left|\left|F\right|\right|\right|$ the number of $3$-cells $F$ is made of.
Definition 3.1. A polygraphic interpretation of a polygraphic program $\mathcal{P}$ consists into a mapping of each $2$-path $f$ with $m$ inputs and $n$ outputs onto two monotone maps $f_{*}:\mathbb{N}^{m}\to\mathbb{N}^{n}$ and $[f]:\mathbb{N}^{m}\to\mathbb{N}$, such that the following conditions are satisfied: • For every $1$-path $x$ of length $n$, we have $x_{*}=\operatorname{Id}_{\mathbb{N}}^{n}$ and $[x]=0$. • For every $2$-paths $f$ and $g$, the following equalitities hold when defined: – $(f\star_{0}g)_{*}(\vec{x},\vec{y})=(f_{*}(\vec{x}),g_{*}(\vec{y}))\>$ and $\>[f\star_{0}g](\vec{x},\vec{y})=[f](\vec{x})+[g](\vec{y})\>$; – $(f\star_{1}g)_{*}(\vec{x})=g_{*}(f_{*}(\vec{x}))\>$ and $\>[f\star_{1}g](\vec{x})=[f](\vec{x})+[g](f_{*}(\vec{x}))$. Given an interpretation and a $2$-cell $\varphi$, we denote by $\varphi^{j}_{*}$ the $j^{\text{th}}$ component of the map $\varphi_{*}$. An interpretation of $\mathcal{P}$ generates a binary relation denoted by $\succ$: it is defined, on $2$-paths $f$ and $g$ with the same $2$-source and the same $2$-target, by $f\succ g$ when the two inequalities $f_{*}(\vec{i})\geq g_{*}(\vec{i})$ and $[f](\vec{i})>[g](\vec{i})$ hold for every possible family $\vec{i}$ of natural numbers. An interpretation is compatible with a $3$-cell $\alpha$ when $s_{2}(\alpha)\succ t_{2}(\alpha)$ and weakly compatible with $\alpha$ if $s_{2}(\alpha)\succeq t_{2}(\alpha)$.
Definition 3.5. We denote by $\mathbb{N}[x_{1},\cdots,x_{n}]$ the algebra of polynomials in $n$ variables and coefficients in $\mathbb{N}$. Let $\mathcal{P}$ be a polygraphic program. A polygraphic interpretation is simple when the following conditions are met: • For any $2$-cell $\varphi$ with $m$ inputs and $n$ outputs, the maps $\sum_{j=1}^{n}\varphi_{*}^{j}$ and $[\varphi]$ are in $\mathbb{N}[x_{1},\dots,x_{m}]$. • If $\gamma$ is a constructor with $n$ inputs, then $\gamma_{*}=\sum_{i=1}^{m}x_{i}+a_{\gamma}$, with $a_{\gamma}>0$, and $[\gamma]=0$. Moreover, we assume that there exists a $a\in\mathbb{N}^{*}$ bounding all the $a_{\gamma}$’s. • On structure $2$-cells, one has $\raisebox{-3.556594pt}{\includegraphics[]{tau.eps}}(i,j)=(j,i)$ and $\raisebox{-2.845276pt}{\includegraphics[]{delta.eps}}(i)=(i,i)$. Moreover, structure cells produce no heat: $\left[\raisebox{-3.556594pt}{\includegraphics[]{delta.eps}}\right](i)=0,\left[% \raisebox{-3.556594pt}{\includegraphics[]{tau.eps}}\right](i,j)=0,\left[% \raisebox{-3.556594pt}{\includegraphics[]{epsilon.eps}}\right](i)=0$. • For every function $\varphi$ with $m$ inputs and $n$ outputs and for every family $(i_{1},\dots,i_{m})$ of natural numbers, we have $\sum_{j=1}^{n}\varphi^{j}_{*}(i_{1},\dots,i_{m})\>\geq\>i_{1}+\cdots+i_{m}$. A polygraphic program is called simple when the $2$-targets of its computation $3$-cells contain at most $K$ structure $2$-cells, for some fixed $K$, and when it admits a simple polygraphic interpretation which is compatible with all of its computation $3$-cells.
Definition 2.1. A monoidal $\mathit{3}$-polygraph is a composite object consisting of cells, paths and compositions organized into dimensions. Dimension $\mathit{1}$ contains elementary sorts called $\mathit{1}$-cells and represented by wires. Their concatenation $\star_{0}$ yields product types called $\mathit{1}$-paths and pictured as juxtaposed vertical wires. The empty product $\ast$ is also a $1$-path, represented by the empty diagram. Dimension $\mathit{2}$ is made of operations called $\mathit{2}$-cells, with a finite number of typed inputs and outputs. They are pictured as circuit gates, with inputs at the top and outputs at the bottom. Using all the $1$-cells and $2$-cells as generators, one builds circuits called $\mathit{2}$-paths, using the following two compositions: $\star_{1}$$=$$f$$f$$g$$g$$f$$g$$=$$f$$g$$\star_{0}$ The constructions are considered modulo some relations, including topological deformation: one can stretch or contract wires freely, move $2$-cells, provided one does not create crossings or break wires. Each $2$-cell and each $2$-path $f$ has a $1$-path $s_{1}(f)$ as input, its $\mathit{1}$-source, and a $1$-path $t_{1}(f)$ as output, its $\mathit{1}$-target. The compact notation $f:s_{1}(f)\Rightarrow t_{1}(f)$ summarizes these facts. Dimension $\mathit{3}$ contains rewriting rules called $\mathit{3}$-cells. They always transform a $2$-path into another one with the same $1$-source and the same $1$-target. Using all the $1$-cells, $2$-cells and $3$-cells as generators, one can build reductions paths called $\mathit{3}$-paths, by application of the following three compositions, defined for $F$ going from $f$ to $f^{\prime}$ and $G$ going from $g$ to $g^{\prime}$: $F\star_{0}G$ goes from $f\star_{0}g$ to $f^{\prime}\star_{0}g^{\prime}$; when $t_{1}(f)=s_{1}(g)$, then $F\star_{1}G$ goes from $f\star_{1}g$ to $f^{\prime}\star_{1}g^{\prime}$; when $f^{\prime}=g$, then $F\star_{2}G$ goes from $f$ to $g^{\prime}$. These constructions are identified modulo some relations, given in [7], where their $3$-dimensional nature was explained. The relations allow one to freely deform the constructions in a reasonable way: in particular, they identify paths that only differ by the order of application of the same $3$-cells on non-overlapping parts of a $2$-path. A $3$-path is elementary when it contains exactly one $3$-cell. Each $3$-cell and each $3$-path $F$ has a $2$-path $s_{2}(F)$ as left-hand side, its $\mathit{2}$-source, and a $2$-path $t_{2}(F)$ as right-hand side, its $\mathit{2}$-target. The notation $F:s_{2}(F)\Rrightarrow t_{2}(F)$ stands for these facts. For monoidal $3$-polygraphs, rewriting notions are defined in a similar way as for term rewriting systems, with terms replaced by $2$-paths, reduction steps by elementary $3$-paths and reduction paths by $3$-paths [6]. Hence, a normal form in a polygraph $\mathcal{P}$ is a $2$-path $f$ which is the $2$-source of no elementary $3$-path. The polygraph $\mathcal{P}$ terminates when it does not contain infinite families $(F_{n})_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$ of elementary $3$-paths such that $t_{2}(F_{n})=s_{2}(F_{n+1})$ for all $n$. Other rewriting properties, such as confluence or convergence are also defined in an intuitive way.
Definition 2.3. A polygraphic program is a monoidal $3$-polygraph such that: • Its $2$-cells are divided into structure $\mathit{2}$-cells, constructors and functions. The structure $2$-cells consist of one $\raisebox{-3.556594pt}{\includegraphics[]{tau.eps}}:\xi\star_{0}\zeta% \Rightarrow\zeta\star_{0}\xi$ for each pair of $1$-cells $(\xi,\zeta)$, plus one $\raisebox{-3.556594pt}{\includegraphics[]{delta.eps}}:\xi\Rightarrow\xi\star_{% 0}\xi$ and one $\raisebox{-3.556594pt}{\includegraphics[]{epsilon.eps}}:\xi\Rightarrow\ast$ for each $1$-cell $\xi$. The constructors are $2$-cells such with a $1$-cell as $1$-target. The functions are any $2$-cells. • Its $3$-cells are divided between structure $\mathit{3}$-cells and computation $\mathit{3}$-cells. The structure $3$-cells are given, for every constructor $\raisebox{-3.556594pt}{\includegraphics[]{phi.eps}}:x\Rightarrow\xi$ and every $1$-cell $\zeta$, by: $x$$\zeta$$\zeta$$\xi$$\zeta$$x$$\xi$$\zeta$$x$$\xi$$\xi$$x$$\xi$$\xi$$x$$\Rrightarrow$$\Rrightarrow$$\Rrightarrow$$\Rrightarrow$$x$$x$$\zeta$$\zeta$$\xi$$x$$\zeta$$\xi$$\zeta$ The $2$-targets of the $3$-cells of $\Delta_{3}^{2}$ use structure $2$-paths built from the structure $2$-cells by using the following structural induction rules: $\ast$$\ast$$\xi$$=$$\xi$$\ast$$\xi$$=$$\xi$$=$$\xi\star_{0}x$$\zeta$$\zeta$$\xi$$x$$x\star_{0}\xi$$x$$\xi$$\ast$$=$$\ast$$=$$=$$\xi$$x$$=$$x\star_{0}\xi$$\zeta$$\zeta$$\xi$$x$$\ast$$x\star_{0}\xi$$=$ The computation $3$-cells are $3$-cells whose $2$-source is of the shape $t\star_{1}\varphi$, with $\varphi$ a function $2$-cell and $t$ a $2$-path built only with $1$-cells and constructors. Furthermore, there is a finite constant that bounds the number of structure $2$-cells in the $2$-target of each computation $3$-cell. • For the present study, we assume that there exists a procedure to perform each step of computation: more formally, for every $3$-path $F:f\to g$ containing exactly one $3$-cell, the map giving $g$ from the pair $(f,F)$ is computable in polynomial time.
Definition 1 (E. Getzler [2]) An $L_{\infty}$-algebra ${\cal L}$ is nilpotent if the lower central filtration of ${\cal L}$ terminates, that is, if ${\cal F}^{i}_{lc}{\cal L}=0$ for $i\gg 0$ .
Definition 3 $L_{\infty}$-morphisms $F$ and ${\mathaccent 869{F}}$ from ${\cal L}$ to ${\cal L}^{\diamond}$ are called homotopic if the corresponding Maurer-Cartan elements of the $L_{\infty}$-algebra ${\cal U}$ (3.9) are equivalent.
Definition 2 (E. Getzler [2]) A Maurer-Cartan $\pi$ of a pronilpotent $L_{\infty}$-algebra $({\cal L},Q)$ is a degree $1$ element of ${\cal L}$ satisfying the equation $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{n!}Q_{n}(\pi,\pi,\dots,\pi)=0\,.$
Definition 4.3. We say that a concrete category ${\mathcal{C}}$ supports elementary embeddings if, for every elementary embedding $j\colon V\to M$ and all objects $X$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$, the restriction $j\restriction X\colon X\to j(X)$ underlies a morphism of ${\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 6. Assume that $A$ is just a vector space over $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$ with a derivation $\partial$ which extends the derivation on $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$ equipped with $\Delta$ and $\varepsilon$ commuting with $\partial.$ In this case $A$ is called a differential coalgebra. When, in addition, $A$ has $S,$ it is called a differential bialgebra.
Definition 2. A neutral differential Tannakian category $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ over a $\partial$-field $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$ of characteristic zero is a (1) rigid (2) abelian (3) tensor category such that $\operatorname{\bf End}(\underline{1})$ is the field $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$ supplied with an (1) exact (2) faithful (3) $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-linear (4) tensor fiber functor $\omega:\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}\to\operatorname{\mathcal{V}}$ (see Definition 1); with a functor $F:X\mapsto X^{(1)},$ intertwining1This means that there is a functorial in $X$ isomorphism $\omega\left(X^{(1)}\right)\cong\omega(X)^{(1)}$. with $\omega$: $F_{\operatorname{\mathcal{V}}}\circ\omega=\omega\circ F_{\operatorname{% \mathcal{C}}},$ where the subscripts $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ and $\operatorname{\mathcal{V}}$ indicate on which category the functor $F$ acts2In Section 5 we will make use of $F^{p}$ on $\operatorname{\mathcal{V}}$ for $p>1$ for computational purposes.. Also, for each $X\in\operatorname{\mathcal{O}b}(\operatorname{\mathcal{C}})$ there must be an inclusion (a morphism with the trivial kernel) $i:X\to X^{(1)}$ and surjection $\phi:X^{(1)}\to X$ morphisms in $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, so that the sequence $\begin{CD}0@>{}>{}>X@>{i}>{}>X^{(1)}@>{\phi}>{}>X@>{}>{}>0\end{CD}$ is exact and is mapped by the fiber functor $\omega$ to the corresponding exact sequence in the category $\operatorname{\mathcal{V}}$: $\begin{CD}0@>{}>{}>\omega(X)@>{i}>{}>\omega(X)^{(1)}@>{\varphi}>{}>\omega(X)@>% {}>{}>0\end{CD},$ where the $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-linear maps $i$ and $\varphi$ are defined in (1) and (3), respectively. Moreover, we require that the differential structure respects tensor products (“product rule”), that is, for the natural $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-linear map $(\omega(X)\otimes\omega(Y))^{(1)}\to\omega(X)^{(1)}\otimes\omega(Y)^{(1)}$ mapping $\displaystyle 1\otimes(v\otimes u)$ $\displaystyle\mapsto(1\otimes v)\otimes(1\otimes u),$ $\displaystyle\partial\otimes(v\otimes u)$ $\displaystyle\mapsto(\partial\otimes v)\otimes(1\otimes u)+(1\otimes v)\otimes% (\partial\otimes u)$ there exists a corresponding morphism in the category $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ $\begin{CD}(X\otimes Y)^{(1)}\\ @V{}V{}V\\ X^{(1)}\otimes Y^{(1)}\end{CD}\xrightarrow{\quad\omega\quad}\begin{CD}(\omega(% X)\otimes\omega(Y))^{(1)}\\ @V{}V{}V\\ \omega(X)^{(1)}\otimes\omega(Y)^{(1)}\end{CD}$ Also, we require that there exists a morphism $g_{X}:(X^{*})^{(1)}\to{X^{(1)}}^{*}$ satisfying the following commutative diagram: $\begin{CD}X^{*}@>{i_{X^{*}}}>{}>(X^{*})^{(1)}@>{\phi_{X^{*}}}>{}>{X^{*}}\\ @V{}V{\operatorname{id}}V@V{}V{g_{X}}V@V{}V{\operatorname{id}}V\\ X^{*}@>{{\phi_{X}}^{*}}>{}>\left(X^{(1)}\right)^{*}@>{{i_{X}}^{*}}>{}>{X^{*}}% \end{CD}$ such that the $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-linear isomorphism $\omega(g_{X}):\omega(X^{*})^{(1)}\to\omega\left(X^{(1)}\right)^{*}$ is of the form: $\begin{CD}\omega(X)^{*}@>{i_{\omega(X)^{*}}}>{}>(\omega(X)^{*})^{(1)}\cong% \omega(X)^{*}\oplus\omega(X)^{*}@>{\varphi_{\omega(X)^{*}}}>{}>{\omega(X)^{*}}% \\ @V{}V{\operatorname{id}}V@V{}V{\omega(g_{X})}V@V{}V{\operatorname{id}}V\\ \omega(X)^{*}@>{\varphi_{\omega(X)}^{*}}>{}>\left(\omega(X)^{(1)}\right)^{*}% \cong(\omega(X)\oplus\omega(X))^{*}@>{i_{\omega(X)}^{*}}>{}>{\omega(X)^{*}}% \end{CD}$ with the map $\omega(g_{X})$ respecting the given splittings into direct sums.
Definition 3. We define $V\otimes X=\{[(X^{n})_{\alpha},\phi_{\beta,\alpha}]\>|\>\alpha:(\operatorname{% \bf k_{0}}0^{n})\cong V\},$ where $(X^{n})_{\alpha}:=X\oplus\ldots\oplus X$ and $\phi_{\beta,\alpha}:(X^{n})_{\alpha}\to(X^{n})_{\beta}$ is defined by $\beta^{-1}\circ\alpha$ acting as an element of $\operatorname{\bf GL}_{n}(\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0).$
Definition 8. An affine differential algebraic group scheme $G$ is called a linear differential algebraic group if there exists an imbedding: $G\to\operatorname{\bf GL}_{n}$ for some $n\in\operatorname{\mathbb{Z}}_{\geqslant 1}$.
Definition 1. The category $\operatorname{\mathcal{V}}$ over a $\partial$-field $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$ is the category of finite dimensional vector spaces over $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$: (1) objects are finite dimensional $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-vector spaces, (2) morphisms are $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-linear maps; with tensor product $\otimes,$ direct sum $\oplus,$ dual $*,$ and additional operations: $F^{p}:V\mapsto V^{(p)}:=\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0[\partial]_{\leqslant p}% \otimes V,$ which we call differentiation (or prolongation) functors. If $\varphi\in\operatorname{Hom}(V,W)$ then we define $F^{p}(\varphi):V^{(p)}\to W^{(p)},\ \varphi(\partial^{q}\otimes v)=\partial^{q% }\otimes\varphi(v),\ 0\leqslant q\leqslant p.$ Here, $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0[\partial]_{\leqslant p}$ is considered as the right $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-module of differential operators up to order $p$ and $V$ is viewed as a left $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-module. We denote $F^{1}$ simply by $F$.
Definition 9. For a $\partial$-$\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-algebra $R$ we define a group $\operatorname{\bf Aut}^{\otimes,\partial}(\omega)(R)$ to be the set of sequences $\lambda(R)=(\lambda_{X}\>|\>X\in\operatorname{\mathcal{O}b}(\operatorname{% \mathcal{C}}))\in\operatorname{\bf Aut}^{\otimes,\partial}(\omega)(R)$ such that $\lambda_{X}$ is an $R$-linear automorphism of $\omega(X)\otimes R$ for each object $X$, $\omega(X)\in\operatorname{\mathcal{O}b}(\operatorname{\mathcal{V}})$, that is, $\lambda_{X}\in\operatorname{\bf Aut}_{R}(\omega(X)\otimes R)$, such that • for all $X_{1},$ $X_{2}$ we have $\displaystyle\lambda_{X_{1}\otimes X_{2}}=\lambda_{X_{1}}\otimes\lambda_{X_{2}},$ • $\lambda_{\underline{1}}$ is the identity map on $\underline{1}\otimes R=R$, • for every $\alpha\in\operatorname{Hom}(X,Y)$ we have $\displaystyle\lambda_{Y}\circ(\alpha\otimes\operatorname{id}_{R})=(\alpha% \otimes\operatorname{id}_{R})\circ\lambda_{X}:\omega(X)\otimes R\to\omega(Y)% \otimes R,$ • for every $X$ we have $\displaystyle\partial\circ\lambda_{X}=\lambda_{X^{(1)}}\circ\partial,$ • the group operation $\lambda_{1}(R)\cdot\lambda_{2}(R)$ is defined by composition in each set $\operatorname{\bf Aut}_{R}(\omega(X)\otimes R).$
Definition 5. Such a commutative associative $\partial$-$\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-algebra $A$ with unit $1$ and operations $m,$ $\Delta,$ $S,$ and $\varepsilon$ satisfying axioms (8) is called a differential Hopf algebra (or $\partial$-$\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-Hopf algebra).
Definition 4. For an object $T\in\operatorname{\mathcal{O}b}(\operatorname{\mathcal{C}})$ we say that $\Phi\in\operatorname{Hom}(V\otimes X,T)$ if $\Phi=\{\varphi_{\alpha}:(X^{n})_{\alpha}\to T\}$ making possible diagrams with $\phi_{\beta,\gamma}$ commutative. Also, $\Phi\in\operatorname{Hom}(T,V\otimes X)$ if $\Phi=\{(\varphi_{1},\ldots,\varphi_{n})_{\alpha}\},$ $\varphi_{i}:T\to X$ making possible diagrams with $\phi_{\beta,\gamma}$ commutative.
Definition 10. We let (1) an object $M$ of $\operatorname{\mathcal{M}}$ be an object of $\operatorname{\mathcal{V}}$ together with a differential module structure given by $\partial_{x}$ which commutes with $\partial$, (2) morphisms between objects of $\operatorname{\mathcal{M}}$ be those which commute with the action of $\partial_{x}:$ $\operatorname{Hom}(M,N)=\operatorname{Hom}_{\operatorname{\bf k}[\partial_{x}]% }(M,N)$ for all objects $M$ and $N$ of $\operatorname{\mathcal{M}},$ (3) subobjects, $\otimes,$ $\oplus,$ and ${}^{*}$ are as in the category of differential modules [15, Section 2.2], (4) the functors $F^{p}$ are the same as in $\operatorname{\mathcal{V}}$.
Definition 7. A finite dimensional vector space $V$ over $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$ is called a $A$-comodule if there is a given $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$-linear morphism $\rho:V\to V\otimes A,$ satisfying the axioms: $\begin{CD}V@>{\rho}>{}>V\otimes A\\ @V{}V{\rho}V@V{}V{\operatorname{id}_{V}\otimes\Delta}V\\ V\otimes A@>{\rho\otimes\operatorname{id}_{A}}>{}>V\otimes A\otimes A\end{CD}% \qquad\qquad\begin{CD}V@>{\rho}>{}>V\otimes A\\ @V{}V{\operatorname{id}_{V}}V@V{}V{\operatorname{id}_{V}\otimes\varepsilon}V\\ V@>{\sim}>{}>V\otimes\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0\end{CD}$ If $A$ is a differential coalgebra with $\Delta$ and $\varepsilon$ then for a comodule $V$ over $A$ the $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0$ space $\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0[\partial]_{\leqslant i}\otimes V=V^{(i)}$ has a natural $A$-comodule structure $\displaystyle\rho(f\otimes v):=f\otimes\rho(v)$ for $f\in\operatorname{\bf k_{0}}0[\partial]_{\leqslant i}$ and $v\in V.$
Definition 2.4. A $t$-structure on a triangulated category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is a pair $(D^{\geq 0},D^{\leq 0})$ of non-zero full subcategories of ${\mathcal{C}}$ satisfying the following conditions, where we denote $D^{\leq n}=D^{\leq 0}[-n]$ and $D^{\geq n}=D^{\geq 0}[-n]$ (1) $D^{\leq 0}\subseteq D^{\leq 1}$ and $D^{\geq 1}\subseteq D^{\geq 0}$ (2) $\operatorname{Hom}(D^{\leq 0},D^{\geq 1})=0$ (3) $\forall Y\in{\mathcal{C}}$, there exists a triangle $X\to Y\to Z\to X[1]$ with $X\in D^{\leq 0}$ and $Z\in D^{\geq 1}$.
